---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<BaseLayout title="Fasting Guide" description="A practical guide to fasting in the Byzantine tradition — medicine for the soul, not punishment for the body.">

  <section class="article-hero">
    <div class="hero-content">
      <div class="section-label" style="margin-bottom:16px;">Practical Guide</div>
      <h1 class="hero-title" style="font-size:34px;">Fasting in the Byzantine Tradition</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        Medicine for the soul, not punishment for the body.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="article-surface">
    <div class="container--narrow">
      <nav class="breadcrumbs">
        <a href={`${base}/`}>Home</a>
        <span class="sep">›</span>
        <a href={`${base}/tools/`}>Tools</a>
        <span class="sep">›</span>
        <span style="color: var(--beeswax);">Fasting Guide</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="article-body">

        <p class="drop-cap">If "fasting" means punishment, the Byzantine tradition wants to reframe entirely. Fasting in the East is medicine. A tool for healing, not a sentence. The Church Fathers prescribed it because <em>you</em> are hungry for freedom: from compulsion, from appetite, from the tyranny of "I want it, therefore I eat it."</p>

        <p>It is not about food. It is about learning that the body is not in charge. And paradoxically, by disciplining the body, you learn to love it properly: as a partner in the spiritual life rather than an enemy to defeat.</p>

        <h2>The Fasting Calendar</h2>

        <p>The Byzantine year includes roughly 180 fasting days. Nearly half the year. This shocks newcomers.</p>

        <p>But the rhythm is not constant deprivation. It is a pulse: fasting and feasting alternating, giving shape to time itself.</p>

        <div class="fasting-section">
          <h3>The Four Major Fasting Periods</h3>

          <div class="fast-period">
            <div class="fast-period-header">
              <span class="fast-period-name">The Great Fast (Great Lent)</span>
              <span class="tag">40 days before Pascha</span>
            </div>
            <p>The strictest and most important. Begins on Clean Monday (not Ash Wednesday; there are no ashes in the East) and continues through Holy Week. No meat, dairy, fish, wine, or oil on most days. The first week and Holy Week are especially austere. Services change. Music becomes more solemn. The community enters collective repentance.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-period">
            <div class="fast-period-header">
              <span class="fast-period-name">The Apostles' Fast</span>
              <span class="tag">Variable: 1–6 weeks after Pentecost</span>
            </div>
            <p>Begins the Monday after All Saints Sunday and ends June 28, the eve of Saints Peter and Paul. Length varies because Pascha moves. In some years, barely a week. In others, over a month. Generally less strict: fish, wine, and oil often permitted except Wednesdays and Fridays.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-period">
            <div class="fast-period-header">
              <span class="fast-period-name">The Dormition Fast</span>
              <span class="tag">August 1–14</span>
            </div>
            <p>Two weeks preparing for the Feast of the Dormition of the Theotokos (August 15). Strict like Great Lent, though shorter. Fish is permitted on the Feast of the Transfiguration (August 6), which falls in the middle.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-period">
            <div class="fast-period-header">
              <span class="fast-period-name">The Nativity Fast (Philip's Fast)</span>
              <span class="tag">November 15 – December 24</span>
            </div>
            <p>Forty days before Christmas. Starts moderately, with fish permitted on most days, and grows stricter as Christmas approaches. The final days mirror Holy Week's austerity. Called "Philip's Fast" because it begins the day after the Apostle Philip's feast.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2>Fasting Levels</h2>

        <p>Not all fasting days are equal. From strictest to most lenient:</p>

        <div class="fasting-levels">
          <div class="fast-level">
            <div class="fast-level-name">Strict Fast / Xerophagy</div>
            <div class="fast-level-desc">Dry eating: bread, raw fruits and vegetables, nuts, water. No cooked food, no oil. Reserved for the most solemn days: Clean Monday, Holy Friday.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-level">
            <div class="fast-level-name">Fast without Oil</div>
            <div class="fast-level-desc">Cooked food permitted, but without olive oil or any oil. Grains, vegetables, legumes, prepared simply.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-level">
            <div class="fast-level-name">Fast with Wine &amp; Oil</div>
            <div class="fast-level-desc">Cooked food with oil, plus wine in moderation. The standard fasting day for most Wednesdays and Fridays outside major seasons.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-level">
            <div class="fast-level-name">Fish Permitted</div>
            <div class="fast-level-desc">Everything above, plus fish. No meat, dairy, or eggs. Common on feast days within fasting periods: a concession of joy within discipline.</div>
          </div>

          <div class="fast-level">
            <div class="fast-level-name">No Fast</div>
            <div class="fast-level-desc">Eat freely. Feast days, Bright Week (after Pascha), the period between Christmas and Theophany, and other designated fast-free periods.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2>The Weekly Rhythm</h2>

        <p>Even outside the four major seasons, Byzantine Christians fast every <strong>Wednesday</strong> and <strong>Friday</strong>.</p>

        <p><strong>Wednesday:</strong> the betrayal of Christ. <strong>Friday:</strong> the Crucifixion. These two days anchor the week in the Paschal mystery. The standard discipline: abstain from meat, dairy, fish, wine, and oil. In practice, many fast at whatever level their priest blesses.</p>

        <p>Several "fast-free weeks" are scattered through the year, when even Wednesday and Friday fasting is suspended: after Christmas, after Pascha, the week of the Publican and Pharisee before Lent. These exist as reminders. Fasting is not the goal. <em>Freedom</em> is the goal. Fast so that feasting means something. Feast so that fasting means something. The rhythm teaches.</p>

        <h2>A Word About Your Priest</h2>

        <div class="pastoral-note">
          <p><strong>Talk to your priest.</strong> This is not a suggestion. It is the tradition's own instruction.</p>

          <p>The fasting rules as written in the liturgical books are the ideal, the full discipline as practiced in monasteries. Very few laypeople follow them to the letter. The Church does not expect them to. A priest knows the circumstances: health, family, spiritual state. He has the authority to adjust.</p>

          <p>A pregnant woman does not fast like a monk. A person recovering from an eating disorder may not fast at all. A new convert might start with just Wednesdays and Fridays. The goal is growth, not performance.</p>

          <p>The Fathers are blunt: fasting without humility is just a diet.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Getting Started</h2>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with Wednesdays and Fridays.</strong> Give up meat on those two days. Just that. For a month.</li>
          <li><strong>Add the Great Fast.</strong> When Lent comes, try the full fast for at least the first week and Holy Week. Be gentle in between.</li>
          <li><strong>Talk to your priest</strong> about what level fits.</li>
          <li><strong>Don't announce it.</strong> Christ's instruction in Matthew 6 is clear. Fast in secret. No dinner party declarations.</li>
          <li><strong>Combine it with prayer.</strong> Fasting without prayer is just being hungry. The discipline creates space. Use it.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>The tradition does not promise easy. It promises <em>formative</em>. Over time, the practice of saying "no" to appetite trains the capacity to say "yes" to things that matter more. Not because food is bad. Because the human person is made for more than food.</p>

        <h2>Further Reading</h2>

        <p>Alexander Schmemann's <em>Great Lent</em> is the classic theological treatment of fasting in the Eastern tradition. For practical recipes and meal planning, see the many "Orthodox fasting cookbook" options available. The catechism <em>Christ Our Pascha</em> covers fasting in §§ 532–548.</p>

      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-hero {
    padding: 80px 40px 32px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .article-body {
    padding-bottom: 80px;
  }
  .article-body p,
  .article-body li {
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
  .article-body h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--beeswax);
    margin: 48px 0 16px;
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  }
  .article-body h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 21px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--beeswax);
    margin: 36px 0 12px;
  }
  .article-body .drop-cap::first-letter {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 56px;
    float: left;
    color: var(--halo-gold);
    opacity: 0.7;
    line-height: 0.8;
    margin: 8px 14px 0 0;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .article-body ol {
    padding-left: 24px;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }
  .article-body ol li {
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  .fasting-section { margin: 32px 0; }
  .fast-period {
    background: var(--icon-wall);
    border: 0.5px solid var(--gold-10);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 24px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .fast-period-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 12px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }
  .fast-period-name {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 19px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--beeswax);
  }
  .fast-period p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .fasting-levels { margin: 24px 0 32px; }
  .fast-level {
    padding: 16px 0;
    border-bottom: 0.5px solid var(--gold-06);
  }
  .fast-level-name {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 17px;
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--beeswax);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .fast-level-desc {
    font-size: 15px;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .pastoral-note {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--halo-gold);
    background: var(--gold-04);
    border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
    padding: 20px 24px;
    margin: 32px 0;
  }
  .pastoral-note p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  @media print {
    body { background: white; color: black; }
    .article-body p, .article-body li { color: #333; }
    .article-body h2, .article-body h3 { color: #111; }
    .fast-period { border: 1px solid #ccc; background: #fafafa; }
    .fast-period-name { color: #111; }
    .fast-level-name { color: #111; }
    .fast-level-desc { color: #333; }
    .pastoral-note { border-left: 2px solid #666; background: #f5f5f5; }
    .breadcrumbs, nav { display: none; }
    .tag { border: 1px solid #999; color: #333; }
  }
</style>
